To find the Shortest Common Supersequence (SCS) of two strings, we use the concept of Longest Common Subsequence (LCS).

The SCS should contain both strings as subsequences.
To avoid duplication, we:
First compute the LCS
Then merge both strings using the LCS

Compute LCS using DP
Let dp[i][j] = length of LCS of str1[0...i-1] and str2[0...j-1]
Reconstruct SCS from DP table
Start from dp[n][m] and backtrack:
If characters match → include it once
If not:
Move in the direction of larger DP value
Add corresponding character
Append remaining characters
If one string is exhausted, add remaining part of the other
``
  if (str1[i-1] == str2[j-1])
      dp[i][j] = 1 + dp[i-1][j-1];
  else
      dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]);
``
Time Complexity: O(n × m)
Space Complexity: O(n × m)
